title: For Sale:  World War 2 Japanese Type 2 Paratrooper Rifle
postcontent: For your consideration is this Japanese type 2 Paratrooper Rifle. The primary difference between this rifle and the Type 99 was the fact that it had a bolt that locked the two pieces into place rather than being made of a single piece. The purpose for this was to allow the Japanese paratroopers to carry them in a bag while they jumped and then piece it together on the ground. There were only 24000 of these types of rifles made throughout the duration of the war. Compare this to the millions of K98s, M1 Garands, Nagants, and even T99s and you can understand why it’s a unique bird. The rifle still has a full imperial Chrysanthemum as well as it’s original anti aircraft sites. Both halves Match however the bolt is ~50 numbers off from the remainder of the rifle. This is commonly seen on rifles brought back from the Pacific Campaigns as it was common procedures to confiscate the bolt while in transit back to the states. Once back they often just grabbed a random bolt assembly from a large group of readily available ones. This rifle displays well and will be a great addition to any advanced World War 2 firearm collection. I can send additional detailed pictures upon request. Will consider trades for an original WW2 era German Luger or other WW2 era firearms

title: For Sale:  World War 2 Japanese Type 2 Paratrooper Rifle
postcontent: For your consideration is this Japanese type 2 Paratrooper Rifle. The primary difference between this rifle and the Type 99 was the fact that it had a bolt that locked the two pieces into place rather than being made of a single piece. The purpose for this was to allow the Japanese paratroopers to carry them in a bag while they jumped and then piece it together on the ground. A large number of these were captured in 1944 after the Japanese paratroopers made a combat jump against US Forces in the Philippines. There were only 24000 of these types of rifles made throughout the duration of the war. Compare this to the millions of K98s, M1 Garands, Nagants, and even T99s and you can understand why it’s a unique bird. The rifle still has a full imperial Chrysanthemum as well as it’s original anti aircraft sites. Both halves Match however the bolt is ~50 numbers off from the remainder of the rifle. This is commonly seen on rifles brought back from the Pacific Campaigns as it was common procedures to confiscate the bolt while in transit back to the states. Once back they often just grabbed a random bolt assembly from a large group of readily available ones. This rifle displays well and will be a great addition to any advanced World War 2 firearm collection. I can send additional detailed pictures upon request. Will consider trades for an original WW2 era German Luger or other WW2 era firearms
